<span style="font-family:Whisper; font-size:80px; letter-spacing:3px;"> <center> Mental Disconnection </center> </span>
{{Phenomenon Class|frequency=2|effectiveness=4|danger=4}}
<div class="center">

==Overview==
{{Blurimage|file=mybrain.png|caption=Brain|hovertext=...}}
The Mental Disconnection effect primarily affects those explorers who have been to the Backrooms for significant amounts of time, especially on dangerous levels or those with serious psychological effects. It is a brain reaction against accumulated traumatic moments and acts as an overreactive defence system in real life, which then acts as a lethal trap.

When an explorer contracts Mental Disconnection, the brain completely disconnects from the body, leaving it completely paralyzed. It is as if the brain, in a desperate attempt to protect itself from the constant fear and anxiety of the Backrooms, resorts to "shutting down" the connection to the body, preventing any movement even the slightest attempt to shift a foot or a finger. Despite its apparent intent to safeguard the player, this effect leaves them utterly exposed, and they are easy prey for whatever enemy is lurking in the level.

Its effect passes through three consecutive stages, which become increasingly worse and debilitating.

=Phase One=

In the first stage, the explorer will lose physical strength and become severely weaker and exhausted. Dizziness and loss of balance for a short time shall be common, and moving around will be a problem. The phase is, however, very mild, and there isn't any lasting or significant impact in this phase. Most explorers will likely just attribute these symptoms as mere fatigue or stress from their experience in the Backrooms.

=Phase Two=
{{Blurimage|file=BRAIN.png|caption=an x-ray done by [[A.A.E.G.|Λ.λ.∈.G]] to someone who had the Mental disconnection effect while he was in the third phase|hovertext=Do you remember me?|align=Left}}
Phase two brings in progressively more threatening changes. The adventurer experiences abrupt and unaccountable attacks of unconsciousness, lapsing into fits of sleepiness at random for intervals of seconds to up to 30 minutes. Concomitant with these attacks, he or she also struggles through severe episodes of insomnia and cannot sleep even after total exhaustion. Their perception of the world will also begin to alter—colours will appear pale as if they are looking at everything through a gray, dull filter. These dissociative episodes become more and more frequent, which means the brain is starting to disconnect more and more from reality.

=Phase Three=

The final and worst phase can strike at any moment without notice. The explorer will suddenly fall into a state of complete paralysis, losing all motor function and sense of the world around them. They cannot smell, feel, or sense anything physically. But, as descriptions indicate, they remain conscious, stuck to observing their paralyzed body from an outside, third-person perspective. This horrific disease is incurable—no way of recovering from it is known. The explorer is isolated, unable to speak to the world, until their body gradually starves, dehydrates, or is damaged from the outside.

It is widely believed that when the body is dead, the explorer's mind also dies. But because no one has ever returned from this last stage to inform us of what occurs, the destiny of the victims of Mental Disconnection is unknown.

==How to cure or avoid it==

The most effective way to prevent Mental Disconnection is by maintaining a consistent mental and emotional equilibrium. Despite the unpleasant environment of the Backrooms, some measures can successfully reduce the chances of experiencing this effect.

=Prevention=
The key to not falling victim to Mental Disconnection is not being alone to face the horrors of the Backrooms. Having people with one who provide psychological and emotional support can be the difference between mental stability and total collapse. Having companions one does not just share the burden of stress but also keeps reality in check, so the mind doesn't lose hope.

Should friendship be out of the question, self-talk can be a backup system. Talking out thoughts and feelings releases tension and processes through trauma before it is at a crisis level. Trapping fear, tension, and trauma without processing them can be the trigger for phase one of the effect, putting an explorer on a one-way street.

=Managing the Early Symptoms=
If an explorer begins to experience the early signs of Mental Disconnection such as weakness, undue fatigue, or constant dizziness, it is essential to act promptly. The only known way to stop its progression is to confront and heal the underlying traumas before they gain strength. This can be achieved through proper rest, emotional release, meditation, or any other technique that stabilizes the mind in this hostile environment.

But if phase two emerges—defined as involuntary sleep episodes and perceptual dissociation—you can't undo it. By this point, the process of disconnection becomes irreversible, and phase three must ensue ineluctably.

Due to this, mental health and prioritization are just as critical to surviving in the Backrooms as physical survival. Avoiding entities and physical danger is important, but it must also be protected from the gradual breakdown that would send an explorer to an even worse fate than death.

==Discovery==
{{Blurimage|file=zipirili.png|caption=One of the X-rays taken of the explorer.|hovertext=Exploration designated 10A}}
The Mental Disconnection effect was found on an [[A.A.E.G.]] expedition in Level [CENSORED]. A few days after spending time in the level, one explorer began complaining of dizzy spells and extreme fatigue, which led researchers to initially suspect that he was developing the beginnings of [[Phenomenon 35]].

Eventually, a few days later, the adventurer continued to complain about dizziness until, while discussing the level during a conversation with an investigator, the adventurer swooned abruptly for 25 minutes. During the subsequent days, it recurred—that he would fall unconscious and sleep extremely badly.

Around 40 days after the journey began, in another encounter, the explorer unexpectedly stopped talking. The scientists took him to have fainted yet again and gave him 30 minutes. After he failed to respond, the scientists panicked and sent out a rescue mission. When they retrieved him, they found him petrified, his body rigid and impassive like that of a statue.

He was returned to the [[A.A.E.G.]] base for further examination. Tests and X-rays showed no injury internally, but he was left in a completely paralyzed state. Days of experiment and research into the cause came to no answer, until at last the Mental Disconnection effect was finally isolated. As there was no method of cure or reversal discovered, the scientists in the end decide to kill the explorer as a mercy kill.



